Access to School Meals During Covid-19 by Monthly Income

COVID-19 has disrupted the daily incomes and livelihoods of many people. For those in the Bay Area who rely on hospitality services, the closure of restaurants and other amenities has left many without sustaining income. Furthermore, the majority online nature of schooling also means that families with children and young adults can no longer depend on the childcare the schoool provides.

One prominent issue during COVID-19 is food insecurity, especially for families with young children. The Institute for Policy Research (IPR) at Northwestern University revealed that by its estimates, food insecurity was 2-3x for families in the last 6 months. However, many schools have mobilized to continue offering boxed/packed lunches to both its regular students and community members.

This assignments seeks to understand how many people have access to School Meals within the Bay Area. Credits go to BayAreaCommunity.org and unboxproject.org for collecting and maintaining a database of locations of school meal availability around the 9 Bay counties. Using the 2017 LODES data (which comes from ACS data), we can provide a loose estimate for how many people have access to food, presumably for their children, depending on how far they are from the nearest school meals.

We assume that LODES data, which describes the distribution of jobs by race, industry, or income bracket for a demographic, can serve as a proxy for the population of a block group. However, this does not actually track the amount of people/children (who don’t have jobs) that require services, and don’t include folks without jobs or who have lost jobs in their analysis. We also assume that “adequate coverage” is being within a fifteen minute walking distance of school meals, since public transportation for school is no longer an option. Another assumption is that population and job changes by block group have not changed much since 2017 and 2020 before the pandemic, though many folks have shifted homes during the pandemic and may have lost jobs. To calculate the % of the population covered, we also assume that the area of a block group near school meals can also represent the population there. This assumes that people are evenly distributed among the census block group, when in reality, that won’t be the case.

SFBI_data <- read.csv("SFBI_Database.csv") 
head(SFBI_data)
school_meals <- SFBI_data %>% 
  select(c(Name, id, longitude..from.locations..2, latitude..from.locations..2, taxonomy, active, service_area)) %>% 
  filter(
    taxonomy == "School Meals", 
    active == "Open"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    lat = as.numeric(latitude..from.locations..2), 
    long = as.numeric(longitude..from.locations..2)
  ) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("longitude..from.locations..2", "latitude..from.locations..2"), crs = 4326)
bay_county_names <-
  c(
    "Alameda",
    "Contra Costa",
    "Marin",
    "Napa",
    "San Francisco",
    "San Mateo",
    "Santa Clara",
    "Solano",
    "Sonoma"
  )

bay_counties <-
  counties("CA", cb = T, progress_bar = F) %>%
  filter(NAME %in% bay_county_names) 
leaflet() %>% 
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  addCircleMarkers(
    data = school_meals,
    radius = 1,
    label = ~Name
  )
walk_15min <- mb_isochrone(
  school_meals,
  profile = "walking",
  time = 15
)

school_meals_walk_15min <-
  school_meals %>% 
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% 
  cbind(walk_15min$geometry) %>% 
  st_as_sf()
leaflet() %>% 
  addMapboxTiles(
    style_id = "streets-v11",
    username = "mapbox"
  ) %>%
  addPolygons(
    data = school_meals_walk_15min,
    label = ~Name
  )

The map above shows the radius of a 15-min walking distance from a school meal service sit in the Bay Area. It provides an initial visual estimate for parts of the area better covered than others.

ca_bg <- block_groups("CA", cb = T, progress_bar = F)

bay_bg <- 
  ca_bg %>% 
  st_centroid() %>% 
  .[bay_counties, ] %>% 
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% 
  left_join(ca_bg %>% select(GEOID)) %>% 
  st_as_sf() %>% 
  st_transform(26910) %>% 
  mutate(original_area = st_area(.))
bay_isochrone_intersect <-
  bay_bg %>% 
  st_intersection(
    school_meals_walk_15min  %>% 
      st_union() %>% 
      st_transform(26910)
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    leftover_area = st_area(.),
    perc_area = leftover_area / original_area
  ) %>% 
  st_transform(4326)

leaflet() %>% 
  addMapboxTiles(
    style_id = "streets-v11",
    username = "mapbox"
  ) %>%
  addPolygons(
    data = bay_isochrone_intersect, 
  )

The graphic above layers on the census block groups onto the previous isochrones to show what block groups (or parts of block groups) are within 15 minutes walking distance of school.

bay_rac <-
  ca_rac %>% 
  filter(
    h_bg %in% bay_bg$GEOID
  ) %>% 
  select(
    c("C000","CE01","CE02", "CE03", "h_bg")
  ) %>% 
  group_by(h_bg) %>% 
  summarise(
    total_jobs = sum(C000), 
    income_1250_jobs = sum(CE01),  #makes <= $1250 monthly 
    income_1251_to_3333_jobs = sum(CE02), #makes $1251 - $3333 monthly 
    income_3333_job = sum(CE03) #makes $3333 monthly 
  ) 

bay_rac_iso <- 
  bay_rac %>% 
  right_join(bay_isochrone_intersect, by = c("h_bg" = "GEOID")) %>% 
  mutate(
    coverage = total_jobs*perc_area,
    coverage_1250 = income_1250_jobs*perc_area,
    coverage_1251_to_3333 = income_1251_to_3333_jobs*perc_area, 
    coverage_3333 = income_3333_job*perc_area
  ) 
bay_covered <- sum(bay_rac_iso$coverage, na.rm = TRUE)

bay_coverage <- sum(bay_rac_iso$coverage, na.rm = TRUE)/sum(bay_rac$total_jobs, na.rm = TRUE)

bay_lowtier <- sum(bay_rac_iso$coverage_1250, na.rm = TRUE)/sum(bay_rac$income_1250_jobs, na.rm = TRUE)

bay_medtier <- sum(bay_rac_iso$coverage_1251_to_3333, na.rm = TRUE)/sum(bay_rac$income_1251_to_3333_jobs, na.rm = TRUE)

bay_hightier <- sum(bay_rac_iso$coverage_3333, na.rm = TRUE)/sum(bay_rac$income_3333_job, na.rm = TRUE)

paste0("Total Number of People Covered: ", bay_covered, ", % Coverage: ", bay_coverage )
## [1] "Total Number of People Covered: 1427045.77050735, % Coverage: 0.426638925713797"
paste0("% With Monthly Income Under $1250: ", bay_lowtier)
## [1] "% With Monthly Income Under $1250: 0.443088839302603"
paste0("% With Monthly Income of $1251-$3333: ", bay_medtier)
## [1] "% With Monthly Income of $1251-$3333: 0.465250489532086"
paste0("% With Monthly Income Above $3333: ", bay_hightier)
## [1] "% With Monthly Income Above $3333: 0.409228994146653"

About 1.4 million people (nearly 43%) of Bay Area residents live near school meals. Given that this number may not include food banks and assisted care centers, this may be a slight underestimate. The percent coverage may be even higher if folks are willing and able to drive or use public transportation to reach these food resources. It would be expected that less schools would be open, but the recent openings in California due to more steady COVID-19 cases as well as the way schools have had more time to plan for the fall quarter may explain the substantial coverage of school meals for students.

There is a not a clear trend by income level that being higher or lower income (in terms of LODES data tiers) lends itself to food access. For example, the highest LODES data tier had the least access (40% versus 43 or 46%). In general, there was little variation between coverage based on monthly income. It is possible to say that lower-medium tiered income areas see a greater need to provide school meals, given the lowered financial stability of some of its constituents. However, one drawback of the LODES data is that the income tiers are not representative of the data. The lowest tier reflects a yearly income of <$15,000, while the highest tier reflects a yearly income of about 40,000. In the case of the Bay Area, in which the median income is 3 figures in some cities, the majority of the population would be in the third bracket, which could reflect the lower coverage - there is a wide array of incomes it describes. Also, using LODES data (identifying population by jobs) is not a great proxy for families who have children - it is hard to use job bracket to identify the residents who may need school services most.
